        <div class="cd-faq-items">
            <ul id="drive" class="cd-faq-group">
                <li class="cd-faq-title"><h2>Driving into Russia</h2></li>
                <li>
                    <a class="cd-faq-trigger" href="#0">Before departure</a>
                    <div class="cd-faq-content">


                        <p>
                            Make sure all your car papers are in order. To drive in Russia, you will need to bring:
                        </p>

                        <ul>
                            <li>
                                Your driver’s license or temporary permit
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                Your car registration documents
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                Basic auto insurance policy or a Green Card (the international auto insurance policy).
                            </li>
                        </ul>

                        <p>Your driver’s license must conform to the provisions of the 8 November 1968 Vienna Convention
                            on
                            Road Traffic, namely: all information on the license has to be in Latin letters or
                            transliterated in Latin script. A non-conforming license has to be translated into Russian
                            and
                            notarized. The driver’s name has to be on the auto insurance policy, or it has to be an “any
                            driver” policy. If you will be driving through other states, find out what their traffic
                            regulations are as they may be different from the Russian regulations.</p><br>
                    </div> <!-- cd-faq-content -->
                </li>

                <li>
                    <a class="cd-faq-trigger" href="#0">Crossing the frontier</a>
                    <div class="cd-faq-content">
                        <p>
                            Make sure your license plate only has letters of the Latin alphabet when crossing the
                            border into Russia. At entry into Russia, you are required to complete a customs
                            declaration of the temporary importation of your vehicle for the entire duration of your
                            stay in Russia. Keep this declaration: you will need it again when you cross the
                            frontier out of Russia.
                        </p>
                    </div> <!-- cd-faq-content -->
                </li>

                {% embed 'GuideBundle:component:faq-item.html.twig' %}
                    {% block faq_title %}
                        Russian traffic regulations
                    {% endblock %}
                    {% block faq_content %}
                        <p>
                            Russia’s traffic regulations are for the most part the same as the regulations effective
                            elsewhere in Europe, with a few exceptions. You have to wait for your green light to
                            drive at a signal-controlled intersection. You cannot take a right on a red light: you
                            have to wait for the general green, or the green arrow on the additional traffic light
                            module (where applicable). The idea to let drivers turn right on a red light has been
                            under consideration for a few years. For now, however, this idea is on trial at a few
                            intersections in Moscow, which are sign-posted accordingly. &nbsp;&nbsp;<br>
                        </p>

                        <br>
                        <a href="http://www.consultant.ru/document/cons_doc_LAW_2709/824c911000b3626674abf3ad6e38a6f04b8a7428/">Russian
                            traffic regulations </a><br>
                        <a href="http://www.garant.ru/doc/busref/spr_dtp/">Fines for traffic violations</a><br>
                    {% endblock faq_content %}
                {% endembed %}

            </ul> <!-- cd-faq-group -->

            <ul id="roads" class="cd-faq-group">
                <li class="cd-faq-title"><h2>Russian Roads</h2></li>
                {% embed 'GuideBundle:component:faq-item.html.twig' %}
                    {% block faq_title %}
                        Types of roads
                    {% endblock %}
                    {% block faq_content %}
                        <p>
                            There are three types of roads in Russia in terms of traffic conditions: regular roads,
                            speedways and highways. The differences between these three types of roads include speed
                            limits and the number of adjoining secondary roads. Russian roads are subsumed under five
                            types by significance, each marked with its own alphabetic-numeric code. The roads that are
                            part of the European road system are coded with the prefix E and a number. Federal roads
                            have the prefix M plus a number. The prefix A with a number stands for a regional road. The
                            prefix P with a number marks an inter-borough road. Other local roads are marked H with a
                            number.
                        </p>

                    {% endblock faq_content %}
                {% endembed %}

                {% embed 'GuideBundle:component:faq-item.html.twig' %}
                    {% block faq_title %}
                        Toll roads
                    {% endblock %}
                    {% block faq_content %}

                        <p>
                            Russia has a good system of toll highways, which offer the benefits of improved paving and
                            greater speed limits. For a long-distance trip, it may be advisable to purchase a
                            transponder linked to your personal account, so you won’t have to stop to pay at the toll
                            booths – the crossbar will rise automatically for you.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            There is a toll section between the 15th and 58th kilometres on the Moscow-Saint&nbsp;Petersburg
                            route M11. The toll will depend on the time of the day and the day of the week.<br>
                            There is another toll section for the detour around the town of Vyshni Volochek. They take
                            cash or bank card. &nbsp;
                        </p>
                        There are seven toll sections on route M4 between Moscow Rostov-on-Don. The tolls are not the same, and they vary during the day. &nbsp;
                        <br>
                        <br>
                    {% endblock faq_content %}
                {% endembed %}
            </ul> <!-- cd-faq-group -->

            <ul id="pay" class="cd-faq-group">
                <li class="cd-faq-title"><h2>Pay-parking</h2></li>
                {% embed 'GuideBundle:component:faq-item.html.twig' %}
                    {% block faq_title %}Moscow{% endblock %}
                    {% block faq_content %}


                        <p>
                            In Moscow, there is pay-parking inside Third Traffic Ring and on some streets outside the
                            Ring, usually
                            around shopping centres and Metro stations. Pay-parking areas are signposted. Street parking
                            is free on
                            Sundays and public holidays.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Parking rates range from 40 to 200 rubles per hour, depending on the neighbourhood and time
                            of the day. Here
                            is how you pay for your parking in Moscow:
                        </p>
                        <ul>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    use the Moscow Parking mobile app for iOS and Android;
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    send a text message to 7757;
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    use a park’o’mat (bank card only);
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    use voice service by dialling 3210 or the regular city number: +7 (495) 539-5454;
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    pay via your account on <a href="http://parking.mos.ru/">parking.mos.ru</a>;
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    use Yandex.Parking mobile app.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                        <p>
                            When you have parked your car, you have 15 minutes to pay for your parking. The fine for
                            unpaid parking is
                            2500 rubles. If your car was towed, contact the call centre at +7 (495)&nbsp;539-5454, or
                            2310 from your
                            mobile phone.
                        </p>
                        <a href="http://parking.mos.ru/">Pay-parking in Moscow</a> <br>
                    {% endblock %}
                {% endembed %}

                {% embed 'GuideBundle:component:faq-item.html.twig' %}
                    {% block faq_title %}Saint Petersburg{% endblock %}
                    {% block faq_content %}


                        <p>
                            There is pay-parking in the Central District of St. Petersburg, but only inside the
                            perimeter formed by
                            Fontanka River Embankment, Nevsky Prospekt, Ligovsky Prospekt, and Ulitsas Radishcheva,
                            Kirochnaya and
                            Pestelya. However, parking is free in this neighbourhood from 8:01 pm to 7:59 am daily.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Parking costs between 30 and 120 roubles per hour, depending on the neighbourhood and
                            vehicle class. Here is
                            how you pay for your parking in Saint&nbsp;Petersburg:
                        </p>
                        <ul>

                            <li>via a park’o’mat (use an ATM card or a parking ticket: parking tickets are available at
                                the Metro
                                stations Chernyshevskaya, Mayakovskaya and Ploshchad Vosstaniya in the pay-park
                                neighbourhood);&nbsp;
                            </li>

                            <li>use your account on the local parking website;&nbsp;</li>

                            <li>use the Saint Petersburg Parking mobile app for iOS and Android;&nbsp;</li>

                            <li>send a text message to 2722.</li>

                        </ul>
                        <p>
                            When you have parked your car, you have 15 minutes to pay for your parking. The fine for
                            unpaid parking is
                            3000 roubles. If your car was towed in a pay-park area, contact the call centre at +7 (812)&nbsp;417-5000.
                        </p>
                        <a href="https://parking.spb.ru/ru/">Pay-parking in Saint Petersburg</a> <br>
                    {% endblock %}
                {% endembed %}

                {% embed 'GuideBundle:component:faq-item.html.twig' %}
                    {% block faq_title %}Kazan{% endblock %}
                    {% block faq_content %}


                        <p>
                            In Kazan, there is pay-parking in some streets of the central Vakhitovsky District.
                            Pay-parking areas are
                            signposted. Street parking is free from 9:01 pm to 6:59 am on weekdays and weekends, as well
                            as on public
                            holidays.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Parking rates, depending on the location, will vary between 30 and 70 rubles per hour. This
                            is how you pay
                            for your parking in Kazan:
                        </p>
                        <ul>
                            <li>via park’o’mat (use your ATM card or local travel card with e-Wallet feature enabled);
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                        <ul>
                            <li>use your account on the local parking website: <a
                                        href="https://parkingkzn.ru/auth/login">https://parkingkzn.ru/auth/login</a>;
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                        <ul>
                            <li>use the Kazan Parking mobile app for iOS and Android;</li>
                        </ul>
                        <ul>
                            <li>send a text message to 3116.</li>
                        </ul>
                        <p>
                            When you have parked your car, you have 15 minutes to pay for your parking. The fine for
                            unpaid parking is
                            2500 rubles. If your car was towed in a pay-park area, contact the call centre at +7 (843)
                            560-5605.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <a href="https://parkingkzn.ru/ru/">Pay-parking in Kazan</a>
                        </p>
                        <br>
                    {% endblock %}
                {% endembed %}

                {% embed 'GuideBundle:component:faq-item.html.twig' %}
                    {% block faq_title %}Sochi{% endblock %}
                    {% block faq_content %}


                        <p>
                            There is pay-parking in Sochi on a few streets close to the railway station and the seaport
                            in the downtown,
                            and on Ulitsas Kirova, Demokraticheskaya and Lenina in Adler. Pay-parking areas are
                            signposted. Parking is
                            free from 8:01 pm to 7:59 am.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Parking costs 50 rubles an hour. You can pay for your parking:
                        </p>
                        <ul>
                            <li>via a park’o’mat (bank cards only);</li>
                        </ul>
                        <ul>
                            <li>via the Sochi Parking mobile app for iOS and Android;</li>
                        </ul>
                        <ul>
                            <li>by text message to 3116.</li>
                        </ul>
                        <p>
                            When you have parked your car, you have 15 minutes to pay for your parking. The fine for
                            unpaid parking is
                            1000 rubles. If your car was towed in a pay-park area, contact the call centre at +7 (862)
                            296-5987.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <a href="https://sochiparking.ru/ru/">Pay-parking in Sochi</a>
                        </p>
                    {% endblock %}
                {% endembed %}

                {% embed 'GuideBundle:component:faq-item.html.twig' %}
                    {% block faq_title %}Ekaterinburg{% endblock %}
                    {% block faq_content %}


                        <p>
                            In Ekaterinburg, there is pay-parking in the very centre of town, within the perimeter
                            formed by Prospekt
                            Lenina and Ulitsas Moskovskaya, Vostochnaya, Dekabristov and Kuibysheva. &nbsp;&nbsp;
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The parking rate is 30 rubles per hour. You can pay for your parking:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            ● &nbsp;&nbsp;via a park'o'mat (use your ATM card or local EKARTA travel card with e-Wallet
                            feature enabled;
                            cash is not accepted); &nbsp;
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            ● &nbsp;&nbsp;via a QIWI terminal or Frisbi pay-point (cash is accepted with both options);
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            ● &nbsp;&nbsp;via your account on the local pay-parking website: <a
                                    href="https://ek-parking.ru/auth/login">https://ek-parking.ru/auth/login</a>
                            ;
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            ● &nbsp;&nbsp;via the Ekaterinburg Parking mobile app for iOS and Android;
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            ● &nbsp;&nbsp;by text message to 3116.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            When you have parked your car, you have 10 minutes to pay for your parking. The fine for
                            unpaid parking
                            ranges from 1000 to 3000 rubles. If your car was towed in a pay-park area, contact the call
                            centre at +7
                            (343) 287-2700.
                        </p>
                        <br>
                        <a href="https://ek-parking.ru/ru/">Pay-parking in Ekaterinburg</a> <br>
                    {% endblock %}
                {% endembed %}

                {% embed 'GuideBundle:component:faq-item.html.twig' %}
                    {% block faq_title %}Nizhny Novgorod{% endblock %}
                    {% block faq_content %}


                        <p>
                            In the upper part of Nizhny Novgorod, there is pay-parking in some sections of Upper Volga
                            Embankment and on
                            Rozhdestvenskaya Ulitsa, from Blagoveshchenskaya Ploshchad to Ploshchad Narodnogo Yedinstva.
                            On the other
                            side of the Volga, there is pay-parking between Moskovsky Railway Station and Ploshchad
                            Revolutsii.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The parking rate is 50 roubles per hour. You can pay for your parking:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            ● via a park’o’mat (use your ATM card or purchase a pay-parking card at a Russian Mail
                            office or Pechat
                            newsstand);
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            ● via your account on the local pay-parking website: <a href="https://parkovkinn.ru/login">https://parkovkinn.ru/login</a>;
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            ● using the N. Novgorod Parking mobile app for iOS and Android;
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            ● by text message to 7878.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The fine for unpaid parking ranges from 1000 to 2000 roubles. If your car was towed in a
                            pay-park area,
                            contact the call centre at +7 (800) 222-2201.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <a href="http://parkovkinn.ru/map">Pay-parking in Nizhny Novgorod</a>
                        </p>
                        <br>
                    {% endblock %}
                {% endembed %}

                {% embed 'GuideBundle:component:faq-item.html.twig' %}
                    {% block faq_title %}Rostov-on-Don{% endblock %}
                    {% block faq_content %}
                        <p>
